04434nam a22006375i 9781575066950DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750669507 a10.1515/97815750669502doi  a(DE-B1597)584388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBS580.D3bM225 2013 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a222.44061 aMann, Steven T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRun, David, Run! :bAn Investigation of the Theological Speech Acts of David's Departure and Return (2 Samuel 14-20) /cSteven T. Mann. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSiphrut: Literature and Theology of the Hebrew Scriptures ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. How to Do Things with Theological Words -- t2. An Overview of Perspectives on the Function of 2 Samuel 14-20 -- t3. Speech Act Theory and David's Departure and Return -- t4. Theological Words from the Wise -- t5. Theological Words from the Banished -- t6. Theological Words from a Banished King -- t7. Theological Words from Opponents -- t8. Words from a Storyteller -- t9. Words for the Return of a King -- t10. David's Departure and Return as Illocutionary and Perlocutionary Act -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Steven Mann highlights the role of theology in the story of David's departure and return as told in 2 Samuel 14-20. Mann's method of narrative analysis employs a philosophy of language called speech act theory. His primary interest is ways in which speech act theory has been applied to biblical narrative, and he concentrates specifically on speech acts that include theological propositional content, that is, words used to denote God. In this way, Mann analyzes the theological speech acts of the narrative and then suggests a way to view the narrative itself as a speech act.The thesis of this study is that speech act theory illuminates the integral role of theology in the story of David's departure and return. Theology is not merely one aspect of the story but is in fact a catalyst necessary to the plot. Furthermore, the act of telling the story as 2 Sam 14-20 does is the very act of portraying David's faith in Yhwh. David's speech acts demonstrate that he believes that Yhwh is someone who intervenes and who finds ways to bring his banished ones back to him. The narrative portrayal of David's faith can be understood as an illocutionary act, with the potential effect of encouraging an audience, a perlocutionary act. In other words, Man demonstrates that this story can inspire any readers who see this narrative as a story not only about David but about themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066950zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066950423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575066950/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK